===Kansas (Border Showdown in Kansas City, MO)=== {{See also|2008 Kansas Jayhawks football team}} {{Linescore Amfootball| |Road='''Kansas''' |R1=3 |R2=16 |R3=7 |R4=14 |Home=#12/11 Missouri |H1=0 |H2=10 |H3=13 |H4=14 }}
On November 30, offensive coordinator [[Dave Christensen]] accepted the job as head coach for the [[Wyoming Cowboys football|Wyoming Cowboys]] in 2009.<ref>[http://www.stltoday.com/stltoday/sports/stories.nsf/mizzou/story/0EB5B8E1460E90378625751100681E58?OpenDocument Christensen to Wyoming], [[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]], November 30, 2008 {{dead link|date=September 2011}}</ref>
{{-}}
=== Oklahoma (Dr. Pepper Big 12 Championship in Kansas City, MO)=== {{See also|2008 Oklahoma Sooners football team}} {{Linescore Amfootball| |Road=#19/17 Missouri |R1=0 |R2=7 |R3=7 |R4=7 |Home='''#2/4 Oklahoma''' |H1=10 |H2=28 |H3=3 |H4=21 }}
QB [[Chase Daniel]] became the Missouri career total offense yardage leader with 13,256. He entered the game with 12,988&nbsp;yards and had 268 total yards (255 passing, 13 rushing) in the game. He moved ahead of [[Brad Smith (American football)|Brad Smith]] (13,088) and had 13,256 at halftime. Senior CB Tru Vaughns made his first career start. PK [[Jeff Wolfert]] improved his career PAT mark to a perfect 182 of 182. TE [[Chase Coffman]] recorded his 30th career touchdown reception. He was already Missouri's all-time touchdown reception leader. Former walk-on WR Tommy Saunders moved into sixth place on the MU career receptions list. He finished the game with 144 to pass current [[Kansas City Chiefs]]' [[Will Franklin (American football)|Will Franklin]].<ref>[http://mutigers.cstv.com/sports/m-footbl/recaps/120708aab.html Mizzou/Oklahoma Post-Game Notes]</ref>
[[Jeremy Maclin]] leads all of major-college football in all-purpose yards per game with 203.54 (2,646&nbsp;yds. in 13&nbsp;G), over 20&nbsp;yards more than second-place [[Jahvid Best]] ([[California Golden Bears football|California]]).<ref>[http://www.stltoday.com/stltoday/sports/stories.nsf/mizzou/story/A2875B5C782E40058625751F0014CBDF?OpenDocument Maclin says jump to NFL isn't a done deal yet], [[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]], Dec. 14, 2008 {{dead link|date=September 2011}}</ref> <br /> He has 1,221 receiving, 987 kickoff return, 250 rushing, and 188 punt returns yardage.<ref>[http://mutigers.cstv.com/sports/m-footbl/stats/2008-2009/teamcume.html#TEAM.IND Missouri Football "Overall Individual Statistics" ('All Purpose')]</ref>
On December 11, TE [[Chase Coffman]] won the prestigious [[John Mackey (American football)|John Mackey]] [[John Mackey Award|Tight End Award]] as the nation's top [[Tight End]].<ref>[http://mutigers.cstv.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/121108aab.html Coffman Wins John Mackey Tight End Award: Senior Becomes First-Ever Tiger To Win National Position Trophy]</ref>
Through 13 games in 2008, MUâs offense ranks 4th in the nation in passing (340.38 ypg), 6th in total offense (497.46 ypg), 6th in scoring (43.15 ppg) and 8th in pass efficiency (162.69 rating).
On December 12, Pinkel said the new offensive coordinator will be present quarterbacks' coach and recruiting coordinator, [[David Yost]].<ref>[http://mutigers.cstv.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/121208aad.html Yost Tabbed To Take Over As Offensive Coordinator]</ref>
{{clear}}
